of their own play market.=E2=80=9D That makes it educational.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A stablecoin is a crypto thing that is sort of an abst=
ract form of a bank. You go to the stablecoin issuer and deposit $1, and yo=
u get a receipt back =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stablecoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0that says=
 =E2=80=9Cthis is $1.=E2=80=9D And then you can=C2=A0<em>use </em>that=C2=
=A0stablecoin, in crypto contexts =E2=80=94=C2=A0on a blockchain, on a cryp=
to exchange=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0as a dollar. It <em>trades</em>; you can ta=
ke your $1 of stablecoin and buy $1 worth of Bitcoin, and then the person w=
ho sold you the Bitcoin will own your stablecoin. Meanwhile the stablecoin =
issuer has your $1, and invests it, and tries to earn a profit, and the pro=
fit pays for its operating expenses and executive salaries and so forth. An=
d you (or whoever holds the stablecoin) can, generally, hand the stablecoin=
 in to the issuer and get your dollar=C2=A0<em>back=C2=A0</em>on relatively=
 short notice,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[1]</span> =
</a> and then the stablecoin issuer has to come up with the dollar.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all roughly speaking like a deposit =
at a bank, though there are differences.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a>=C2=A0And if you know about banks you will kn=
ow some ways this can go wrong. Two famous ones are:</p><ol style=3D"list-s=
tyle-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">The bank/stablecoin issuer has your money. It gets to inve=
st the money, and it gets to keep the profits.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;"> <span>[3]</span> </a> The more profits it generates from its=
 depositors=E2=80=99=C2=A0money, the more it keeps. On the other hand, if i=
t=C2=A0<em>loses=C2=A0</em>all the money, the depositors bear most of the l=
osses: Most of the issuer=E2=80=99s money belongs to the depositors, so if =
it loses it there=E2=80=99s no more money to make it up to them. So the iss=
uer has incentives to take risk: If the risks pay out, it makes a lot of mo=
ney; if they don=E2=80=99t, somebody else loses a lot of money.</li> <li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There can be a =E2=80=9Crun on the bank.=E2=80=
=9D The stablecoin issuer might invest all your money in very safe things, =
but some of those things are long-term investments, and if=C2=A0<em>everyon=
e=C2=A0</em>demands their money back=C2=A0<em>today</em>, the issuer might =
