d-quarter update, referring to creditor-on-creditor violence. =E2=80=9CIt s=
hould really be thought of as sponsor-on-creditor violence, with select cre=
ditors being offered a choice between being killed or doing something about=
 it.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, one way=
 to think about it is that credit=C2=A0funds are taking money from each oth=
er by doing aggressive =E2=80=9Ccapital solutions=E2=80=9D trades, but anot=
her way to think about it is that private equity sponsors are taking money =
from their creditors by doing aggressive =E2=80=9Cliability management exer=
cises.=E2=80=9D (Those two terms refer, roughly, to who initiates the trade=
: A hedge fund might have a capital solutions business that calls up compan=
ies and says =E2=80=9Chey would you like to stiff your other creditors to b=
orrow more money from us,=E2=80=9D while a company=E2=80=99s advisers might=
 have a liability management team that calls up creditors and says =E2=80=
=9Chey would you like to lend us more money if we stiff our other creditors=
=3F=E2=80=9D) In the sponsor-on-creditor terminology, the credit=C2=A0funds=
 don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to go around killing each other, but=
 their borrowers leave them no choice.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But =
a reader emailed to say:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not cr=
editor on creditor, not sponsor on creditor. =C2=A0In most aggressive LMEs,=
 the company ends up filing. =C2=A0Thus the attorneys get paid for the LME,=
 and get paid for the eventual bankruptcy. =C2=A0It is attorney on creditor=
 violence.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is probably s=
omething to that=3F The creative creditors who lend new money in a liabilit=
y management exercise=C2=A0in exchange for more seniority in the capital st=
ructure get some=C2=A0<em>expected=C2=A0</em>value for themselves: They mov=
e up in seniority, they get promised better terms in exchange for lending n=
ew money. But that value is generally at=C2=A0<em>risk</em>, and if the com=
pany ends up filing for bankruptcy anyway, the favored creditors could stil=
l lose a lot of money. (They probably do better than the disfavored credito=
rs who got =E2=80=9Ckilled=E2=80=9D in the LME, though maybe not if they pu=
t in too much new money.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the cre=
ative=C2=A0<em>advisers=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0bankers and lawyers =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0who help the company, the sponsors and the creditors do the liabil=
ity management exercise get paid in cash, when the LME happens, and if the =
company later goes bankrupt they=E2=80=99re just fine. Broadly speaking the=
se exercises extract money=C2=A0<em>in expectation=C2=A0</em>from some cred=
itors, give some of it=C2=A0<em>in expectation=C2=A0</em>to other creditors=
 and to the company, and give some of it=C2=A0<em>in cash=C2=A0</em>to the =
lawyers. Sometimes none of the expectations work out and only the lawyers d=
o well.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other point here is of course t=
hat the lawyers are the ones who wrote the original credit=C2=A0documents, =
the ones that later lawyers pore over to find loopholes to allow aggressive=
 liability management transactions. If you write porous credit agreements, =
that sets you up for lucrative liability management exercises, which can se=
t you up for a lucrative bankruptcy.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"10=
